00:50:12,808 --> 00:50:16,923
Hello grandma, you're looking very well as always.

813
00:50:17,143 --> 00:50:19,500
You don't look so bad yourself.

814
00:50:19,516 --> 00:50:20,687
Not tired from your trip?

815
00:50:21,250 --> 00:50:23,273
Naw, I feel fine.

816
00:50:23,316 --> 00:50:26,318
Your sure you don't want to go
back to the house first for a nap.

817
00:50:26,383 --> 00:50:29,125
No really, look, I'm good to go.

818
00:50:29,336 --> 00:50:33,672
Oh my. Traditional work pants. You really are ready.

819
00:50:34,854 --> 00:50:37,257
And they're the only ones I brought with me.

820
00:50:37,764 --> 00:50:39,090
Well, look at you.

821
00:50:39,335 --> 00:50:43,327
These days you hardly ever see
the girls around here wearing those.

822
00:50:43,502 --> 00:50:46,705
You look more like a farmer than they do.

823
00:50:46,971 --> 00:50:48,591
She sure does.

824
00:51:11,387 --> 00:51:12,740
Hey, farm girl!

825
00:51:14,975 --> 00:51:16,170
Toshio!

826
00:51:21,546 --> 00:51:24,880
And so I began my second taste of country life.

827
00:51:30,530 --> 00:51:35,716
I always wondered how they produced a vibrant
vivid red from such a simple yellow flower.

828
00:51:36,595 --> 00:51:39,841
According to folklore, before they had protective gloves,

829
00:51:40,059 --> 00:51:43,447
young farm girls would harvest
the pedals with their bare hands.

830
00:51:44,512 --> 00:51:46,861
The thorns could prick them mercilessly

831
00:51:47,088 --> 00:51:49,776
and their blood was said to turn into the deepest crimson.

832
00:51:51,313 --> 00:51:56,557
I imagine those girls unable to afford to paint
they're lips red with the very rouge they had created.

833
00:51:57,971 --> 00:52:01,111
I manage them jealous of the fancy girls from the city.

834
00:52:03,073 --> 00:52:06,484
It took sixty baskets of pedals
to make a handful of rouge.

835
00:52:07,167 --> 00:52:10,988
Ironic that a golden flower, once transformed into red,

836
00:52:11,516 --> 00:52:14,887
was quite literally worth it's weight in gold.

837
00:53:47,425 --> 00:53:48,313
It's amazing,

838
00:53:49,366 --> 00:53:52,649
the pedals were rinsed then crushed into a paste.

839
00:53:53,632 --> 00:53:58,602
With enough air and water the pedals
oxidized and gradually turned more red.

840
00:54:00,170 --> 00:54:04,899
In two or three days the mushed-up
pedals ferment and go completely red

841
00:54:05,344 --> 00:54:06,469
and turn sticky.

842
00:54:09,328 --> 00:54:13,445
After the paste has been pounded in
a mortar and rolled into an egg shape.

843
00:54:13,676 --> 00:54:19,367
It's dried in the sun and finally
it can be used as the bases for rouge.

844
00:54:23,395 --> 00:54:26,661
Even the liquid from pressing
the yellow pedals isn't wasted.

845
00:54:27,136 --> 00:54:30,255
Every last drop is squeezed out and saved.

846
00:54:30,967 --> 00:54:33,919
It is then used for safflower dyeing of cloth.

847
00:54:34,049 --> 00:54:36,696
Dye, dye we are off to dye.

848
00:54:36,804 --> 00:54:39,458
We dip it in the color. Dip it good and let it dry.

849
00:54:39,512 --> 00:54:42,336
Safflower will no longer make us cry.

850
00:54:42,352 --> 00:54:44,700
Those poor village girls way back when.

851
00:54:45,009 --> 00:54:49,083
Would bring color into their world
with this so called waste product.

852
00:54:54,424 --> 00:54:58,132
They would dye cotton and linen bright beautiful pink.

853
00:55:00,776 --> 00:55:01,657
Wow!

854
00:55:04,109 --> 00:55:07,180
Now mechanization has reduced the amount of labor.

855
00:55:07,614 --> 00:55:10,774
But the pedals still need harvesting by hand, every day.

856
00:55:40,783 --> 00:55:44,469
Rouge cakes soon mold, and the flowers wait for no one.

857
00:55:45,489 --> 00:55:48,031
When you look back over the flowers you've picked

858
00:55:48,288 --> 00:55:50,336
suddenly new ones have come into bloom.

859
00:55:52,612 --> 00:55:55,971
In the rainy season your soaked without letup

860
00:55:55,987 --> 00:55:58,828
and sometimes work goes on all night.

861
00:56:02,005 --> 00:56:03,851
The days have flown by,

862
00:56:04,987 --> 00:56:07,859
I'm tired in a deeply satisfying way.

863
00:56:08,500 --> 00:56:12,207
I feel a little like one of
those flower-picking girls of old.

864
00:56:13,424 --> 00:56:16,404
If I'd had the chance to help
out like this when I was a girl,

865
00:56:16,896 --> 00:56:19,037
I'd have written an essay about my own life.

866
00:56:19,559 --> 00:56:21,318
Not just about something I'd read.

867
00:56:37,116 --> 00:56:39,347
Hey mom, can I have 5,000 yen.

868
00:56:39,501 --> 00:56:42,891
¥5,000? For what? Do I look like I'm made out of money?

869
00:56:42,907 --> 00:56:46,108
Mom, no but. Well... You said
you'd buy me some new running shoes.

870
00:56:46,110 --> 00:56:48,226
Running shoes can't cost that much?

871
00:56:48,228 --> 00:56:49,344
Yes, they do.

872
00:56:49,346 --> 00:56:50,206
No, they don't.

873
00:56:50,222 --> 00:56:51,659
Well, Pumas sure do.

874
00:56:52,039 --> 00:56:52,769
Pumas?

875
00:56:52,784 --> 00:56:54,362
Yes Puma.

876
00:56:56,408 --> 00:56:58,665
Well anyway, I've never heard of them.

877
00:56:59,218 --> 00:57:00,773
There must be cheaper ones.

878
00:57:01,514 --> 00:57:03,172
What's wrong with the ones you have now?

879
00:57:03,327 --> 00:57:05,727
Nobody wears those stupid old things now.

880
00:57:05,760 --> 00:57:07,289
You begged me for those.

881
00:57:07,309 --> 00:57:09,350
Everybody is getting Pumas.

882
00:57:09,489 --> 00:57:10,656
Who's everybody?

883
00:57:11,070 --> 00:57:14,509
Kako and Megu and then theirs Yachan and Nonchan.

884
00:57:14,525 --> 00:57:16,359
What? That's only four.

885
00:57:16,784 --> 00:57:19,094
Well, it's more than just them. It's everyone.

886
00:57:19,476 --> 00:57:20,726
I don't think so.

887
00:57:21,148 --> 00:57:22,679
Maybe if you helped out more.

888
00:57:22,695 --> 00:57:24,312
Mom! Mom...

889
00:57:24,328 --> 00:57:26,695
You got him to buy your doll another dress.

890
00:57:27,070 --> 00:57:28,445
It's not even your birthday.

891
00:57:31,588 --> 00:57:33,760
Didn't you say it would only
be for Christmas and birthdays?

892
00:57:34,142 --> 00:57:36,361
Dad, your spoiling Taeko rotten.

893
00:57:37,517 --> 00:57:39,010
Do I spoil you little bear?

894
00:57:39,329 --> 00:57:42,174
All of a sudden, my fifth grade self was back.

895
00:57:43,416 --> 00:57:44,689
But uh...

896
00:57:46,142 --> 00:57:50,705
How come Yaeko got a brand new
kimono? It wasn't even her birthday.

897
00:57:50,721 --> 00:57:51,986
That was for a show.

898
00:57:52,181 --> 00:57:55,142
Your always asking father for little things all the time,

899
00:57:55,188 --> 00:57:57,963
but he buys us one big thing now and then.

900
00:57:58,681 --> 00:57:59,197
Right?

901
00:57:59,489 --> 00:58:00,132
Right.

902
00:58:04,665 --> 00:58:06,723
Taeko, you stop that,

903
00:58:07,365 --> 00:58:09,301
and eat what you are given.

904
00:58:10,703 --> 00:58:12,922
Daddy eats my onions, right dad?

905
00:58:13,292 --> 00:58:13,797
Uh-huh.

906
00:58:15,086 --> 00:58:19,679
What's the big deal anyway, everybody knows
that your gonna get that kimono eventually.

907
00:58:20,436 --> 00:58:21,912
Another hand-me-down.

908
00:58:22,109 --> 00:58:24,687
A lot of kids don't even have hand-me-downs.

909
00:58:25,029 --> 00:58:25,933
Exactly.

910
00:58:25,935 --> 00:58:28,605
Then you can finally give me that enamel handbag.

911
00:58:28,688 --> 00:58:30,703
I thought I told you to give that to her.

912
00:58:30,910 --> 00:58:32,148
You're still hanging on to that.

913
00:58:32,773 --> 00:58:34,734
That's for babies. Give it to her.

914
00:58:42,635 --> 00:58:43,738
No thanks.

915
00:58:45,297 --> 00:58:46,738
I don't even.. Like it.

916
00:58:49,682 --> 00:58:51,636
You don't? Fine I'll keep it.

917
00:58:52,390 --> 00:58:54,440
Taeko, I'm not buying you a new one.

918
00:58:54,602 --> 00:58:55,644
Who cares.

919
00:58:56,467 --> 00:58:57,699
Humph, I'm glad.

920
00:58:57,971 --> 00:59:00,183
Now I get to keep it for sentimental reasons.

921
00:59:00,406 --> 00:59:02,089
Oh yeah! I hate it now!

922
00:59:06,135 --> 00:59:09,135
Next course. Take these away.

923
00:59:09,474 --> 00:59:11,596
You see, they get thrown out.

924
00:59:12,099 --> 00:59:13,487
That is such a waste.

925
00:59:15,249 --> 00:59:17,929
No don't. Don't throw them away!

926
00:59:17,971 --> 00:59:19,161
You should know better.

927
00:59:19,360 --> 00:59:21,877
Eat it your self then it won't go to waste.

928
00:59:23,721 --> 00:59:26,010
All of you girls are so selfish.

929
00:59:38,399 --> 00:59:42,045
Daddy, I need a new enamel bag.

930
00:59:44,280 --> 00:59:46,803
Because Yaeko won't give me hers.

931
00:59:47,134 --> 00:59:49,176
Well, that's because you said you didn't want it.

932
00:59:51,085 --> 00:59:52,752
Yeah, but uh...

933
00:59:53,129 --> 00:59:55,048
You have to stand by what you say.

934
01:00:03,234 --> 01:00:05,139
Go on, hurry and get ready.

935
01:00:08,508 --> 01:00:10,512
Yeah, I think I'm gonna wear these shoes.

936
01:00:12,592 --> 01:00:15,664
Mom, why does she have to come too?

937
01:00:17,077 --> 01:00:19,398
You told me it was gonna be just us.

938
01:00:19,540 --> 01:00:21,618
Just you, me and daddy.

939
01:00:23,139 --> 01:00:24,962
I've done all my homework.

940
01:00:25,640 --> 01:00:27,530
Is there some sort of problem?

941
01:00:27,673 --> 01:00:29,346
We're going out for Chinese.

942
01:00:29,459 --> 01:00:31,271
It's much more fun if we all go.

943
01:00:31,273 --> 01:00:33,923
In that case then, grandma should come with us too.

944
01:00:33,939 --> 01:00:36,670
Grandma says Chinese food is too oily.

945
01:00:36,924 --> 01:00:39,102
If you don't wanna come, you can stay home.

946
01:01:04,577 --> 01:01:06,796
Come on Taeko we're going.

947
01:01:08,352 --> 01:01:09,921
Hurry up you slowpoke.

948
01:01:12,595 --> 01:01:14,846
I can't go, I don't have a purse.

949
01:01:17,026 --> 01:01:19,866
Yaeko, lend your sister your enamel purse.

950
01:01:45,130 --> 01:01:45,855
Here.

951
01:01:47,671 --> 01:01:48,878
Oww-a.

952
01:01:49,233 --> 01:01:50,642
Come on, we're ready.

953
01:01:50,784 --> 01:01:51,944
I'm not going!

954
01:01:52,490 --> 01:01:54,592
Your not. Let's go mother.

955
01:01:55,750 --> 01:01:58,021
Fine you can stay here with your grandma.

956
01:02:04,741 --> 01:02:06,751
Are you not coming my little bear?

957
01:02:07,010 --> 01:02:07,925
Never!

958
01:02:26,609 --> 01:02:27,421
Let's go.

959
01:02:37,175 --> 01:02:38,261
I'm coming!

960
01:02:51,922 --> 01:02:52,963
No shoes!

961
01:02:58,138 --> 01:03:00,041
Stop that! Please stop!

962
01:03:25,495 --> 01:03:26,869
She lost a button.

963
01:03:39,965 --> 01:03:41,530
We stayed home, of course.

964
01:03:42,199 --> 01:03:43,273
My cheek swelled up.

965
01:03:43,395 --> 01:03:46,405
My mom gave me a cold towel but it wouldn't stop stinging.

966
01:03:47,498 --> 01:03:50,007
All that night I lay in my bed wondering..

967
01:03:50,445 --> 01:03:52,019
Why am I being singled out?

968
01:03:52,035 --> 01:03:53,468
I must be adopted.

969
01:03:53,484 --> 01:03:55,585
I was sure of it. Absolutely sure.

970
01:03:56,392 --> 01:03:58,202
I cried myself to sleep that night.

971
01:03:59,481 --> 01:04:02,827
Was that the first time.. That your dad ever hit you?

972
01:04:03,720 --> 01:04:06,030
That was the first and the last.

973
01:04:08,181 --> 01:04:10,127
Dad slaps me sometimes.

974
01:04:10,544 --> 01:04:12,661
Not that often though and not that hard.

975
01:04:13,107 --> 01:04:15,466
It might be better if it happens now and again.

976
01:04:16,137 --> 01:04:19,818
Only once and you wondern' why it had happened just then.

977
01:04:20,663 --> 01:04:22,865
It's hard to believe that you behaved like that.

978
01:04:23,057 --> 01:04:24,688
It just doesn't seem like you.

979
01:04:25,979 --> 01:04:27,723
Well... That was me.

980
01:04:28,272 --> 01:04:30,822
It's all the same, Pumas, onions.

981
01:04:33,098 --> 01:04:35,176
Ah... I feel a lot better now.

982
01:04:35,224 --> 01:04:36,084
Thank you.

983
01:04:36,806 --> 01:04:39,124
Wait a minute! Wait! Your poor mom.

984
01:04:39,140 --> 01:04:40,431
I didn't mean to encourage you.

985
01:04:40,594 --> 01:04:41,726
Take my advice.

986
01:04:41,728 --> 01:04:44,353
Your mom a smart woman. Listen to her.

987
01:04:45,837 --> 01:04:46,783
It's OK.

988
01:04:49,068 --> 01:04:51,406
I'm giving up the Puma anyhow.

989
01:04:52,042 --> 01:04:52,882
Good girl.

990
01:04:53,736 --> 01:04:57,640
Hey, this deserves a bit of ice cream.

991
01:04:57,949 --> 01:04:58,994
Sound good!

992
01:05:17,835 --> 01:05:18,846
Aah.

993
01:05:19,956 --> 01:05:20,493
Huh?

994
01:05:21,597 --> 01:05:22,251
Hey!

995
01:05:24,243 --> 01:05:24,853
Hi.

996
01:05:24,868 --> 01:05:26,203
Not so fast.

997
01:05:27,077 --> 01:05:29,298
They're 100 yen each.

998
01:05:32,907 --> 01:05:32,916
Hey MM77020, are you up for a drive?

999
01:05:32,956 --> 01:05:35,056
Hey Taeko, are you up for a drive?

1000
01:05:35,311 --> 01:05:38,110
I'd like to take you to Zaō tomorrow. Its pretty.

1001
01:05:38,938 --> 01:05:39,696
Zaō?

1002
01:05:39,868 --> 01:05:40,556
Mmm.

1003
01:05:41,516 --> 01:05:43,782
They said you went to a temple
there last time you were here.

1004
01:05:44,697 --> 01:05:47,208
The elders gave me permission. Don't worry.

1005
01:06:12,490 --> 01:06:14,794
The views at mount Zaō was incredible.

1006
01:06:15,200 --> 01:06:16,082
Beautiful.

1007
01:06:16,641 --> 01:06:19,293
But Zaō itself has got a little bit touristy.

1008
01:06:24,722 --> 01:06:26,809
Why haven't you ever gotten married?

1009
01:06:27,262 --> 01:06:27,747
Huh?

1010
01:06:28,674 --> 01:06:30,840
Why, is it that strange that I'm single?

1011
01:06:31,538 --> 01:06:32,324
Ah...

1012
01:06:32,606 --> 01:06:34,036
No, I didn't mean that.

1013
01:06:34,425 --> 01:06:36,793
There are plenty on women in the city who work.

1014
01:06:37,217 --> 01:06:40,153
And I think my single friends
outnumber the ones that are married.

1015
01:06:40,984 --> 01:06:42,403
Oh, really?

1016
01:06:43,063 --> 01:06:43,692
For sure.

1017
01:06:44,508 --> 01:06:45,364
It makes sense.

1018
01:06:46,087 --> 01:06:46,975
It's true.

1019
01:06:48,169 --> 01:06:48,879
Okay.

1020
01:06:49,454 --> 01:06:51,278
It is completely normal.

1021
01:06:57,892 --> 01:06:59,512
So, Toshio...

1022
01:06:59,693 --> 01:07:03,536
When you were small how were you with fractions?

1023
01:07:04,053 --> 01:07:04,629
Huh?

1024
01:07:05,623 --> 01:07:08,551
Where you flip the numerator and denominator,

1025
01:07:08,629 --> 01:07:09,832
did you get that?

1026
01:07:10,165 --> 01:07:12,464
Uh... I don't remember.

1027
01:07:13,260 --> 01:07:15,801
But I don't think I found it very difficult. You?

1028
01:07:16,270 --> 01:07:17,067
Even fractions?

1029
01:07:17,082 --> 01:07:17,562
Mmm.

1030
01:07:18,168 --> 01:07:19,020
Lucky you.

1031
01:07:19,193 --> 01:07:22,051
I bet you don't remember because
you understood it right away.

1032
01:07:22,622 --> 01:07:23,458
Yeah...

1033
01:07:23,627 --> 01:07:25,441
But why do you ask all of a sudden?

1034
01:07:26,293 --> 01:07:29,786
I believe that people who understand
how to divide fractions right away,

1035
01:07:29,823 --> 01:07:31,489
understand life right away too.

1036
01:07:33,288 --> 01:07:35,687
OK, here then, let me give you an example.

1037
01:07:36,176 --> 01:07:38,415
One of my friends was just average in school,

1038
01:07:38,661 --> 01:07:41,835
but she could flip a numerator like that.

1039
01:07:42,334 --> 01:07:45,434
I think people who understood that saw life more clearly.

1040
01:07:45,450 --> 01:07:47,176
She always new she would get married

1041
01:07:47,228 --> 01:07:48,567
and exactly what she'd do.

1042
01:07:49,164 --> 01:07:49,739
Hum...

1043
01:07:50,979 --> 01:07:53,450
But I was terrible at fractions.

1044
01:07:54,235 --> 01:07:57,106
Sometimes I'd just wish that it had been easier for me.

1045
01:08:14,036 --> 01:08:16,356
Uh... You see...

1046
01:08:17,327 --> 01:08:18,889
Before the test...

1047
01:08:18,905 --> 01:08:19,690
Uh...

1048
01:08:20,994 --> 01:08:22,514
We had art class.

1049
01:08:24,061 --> 01:08:25,259
And... we did...

1050
01:08:25,694 --> 01:08:28,045
Uh... we did blow pictures.

1051
01:08:28,231 --> 01:08:29,381
Blow what?

1052
01:08:30,206 --> 01:08:34,202
Well... You spread the paint on the paper and...

1053
01:08:36,680 --> 01:08:38,702
You blow on it to make patterns.

1054
01:08:40,019 --> 01:08:41,241
Oh, I see.

1055
01:08:41,781 --> 01:08:42,350
Then...

1056
01:08:43,776 --> 01:08:44,869
Really hard see.

1057
01:08:45,676 --> 01:08:46,319
See?

1058
01:08:47,302 --> 01:08:48,147
And then?

1059
01:08:48,673 --> 01:08:51,405
My head ached. From doing it all day.

1060
01:08:53,173 --> 01:08:54,499
And blowing so hard.

1061
01:08:54,881 --> 01:08:56,835
And that's why you did so poorly?

1062
01:08:57,487 --> 01:08:59,491
Huh, I guess so.

1063
01:09:00,953 --> 01:09:02,311
Very well then.

1064
01:09:07,843 --> 01:09:10,593
Do you know the right answers to the ones you got wrong?

1065
01:09:10,866 --> 01:09:11,581
Huh?

1066
01:09:11,761 --> 01:09:13,292
The correct answers?

1067
01:09:13,564 --> 01:09:14,269
Uh...

1068
01:09:14,894 --> 01:09:15,921
Hmm.

1069
01:09:16,839 --> 01:09:18,618
Get Yaeko to help you with it.

1070
01:09:19,305 --> 01:09:20,561
Really! Yaeko?!

1071
01:09:21,092 --> 01:09:22,305
Or Nanako.

1072
01:09:23,516 --> 01:09:25,188
If you think that would be better for you.

1073
01:09:28,501 --> 01:09:29,745
I'll ask Nanako.

1074
01:09:51,356 --> 01:09:55,771
Nanako's not back yet. Can I
wait 'til later for her to help me?

1075
01:10:05,387 --> 01:10:07,764
Guess I'll just have to ask Yaeko.

1076
01:10:24,895 --> 01:10:26,309
You can't be serious!

1077
01:10:26,638 --> 01:10:28,794
Mother! Mother!

1078
01:10:31,369 --> 01:10:32,817
What on earth is this?!

1079
01:10:33,676 --> 01:10:35,187
How am I suppose to help her?

1080
01:10:35,208 --> 01:10:38,546
Just do your best. I'm sure you can be patient with her.

1081
01:10:40,801 --> 01:10:42,715
She doesn't understand at all.

1082
01:10:42,731 --> 01:10:44,317
How can I help someone like that?

1083
01:10:44,364 --> 01:10:45,957
I'm sure you can find a way.

1084
01:10:45,973 --> 01:10:47,996
But something is definitely wrong with her

1085
01:10:48,012 --> 01:10:49,407
I said help her!

1086
01:10:50,371 --> 01:10:53,394
Mother... No normal kid could get a mark this low.

1087
01:10:53,517 --> 01:10:55,731
But Taeko is not a normal kid!

1088
01:11:09,859 --> 01:11:12,640
Taeko, your sister's going to help you.

1089
01:11:15,687 --> 01:11:17,918
You got a headache from blowing patterns.

1090
01:11:18,602 --> 01:11:19,882
I understand.

1091
01:11:20,798 --> 01:11:21,572
Taeko.

1092
01:11:23,407 --> 01:11:24,237
Sit down.

1093
01:11:29,401 --> 01:11:31,454
Now, recite your times tables out loud.

1094
01:11:31,620 --> 01:11:33,463
I don't need to prove that to you.

1095
01:11:33,479 --> 01:11:35,065
Just tell me what to do.

1096
01:11:35,580 --> 01:11:37,955
I'm telling you! You need to know your multiplication!

1097
01:11:38,432 --> 01:11:40,714
It's division by fractions.

1098
01:11:41,276 --> 01:11:41,845
Hmm.

1099
01:11:47,461 --> 01:11:52,351
All you have to do is reverse the
numerator and denominator then multiply.

1100
01:11:52,816 --> 01:11:54,313
Didn't they tell you that at school?

1101
01:11:55,648 --> 01:11:56,492
Uh-huh.

1102
01:11:56,617 --> 01:11:58,214
Then why is it all wrong?

1103
01:11:58,550 --> 01:12:01,406
Yaeko, be patient please.

1104
01:12:06,433 --> 01:12:09,173
Why would you divide a fraction by a fraction?

1105
01:12:15,337 --> 01:12:18,867
Dividing two-thirds of an apple into quarter means...

1106
01:12:18,883 --> 01:12:24,200
If you take two-thirds of an
apple and split it into four ways...

1107
01:12:24,960 --> 01:12:27,185
How much apple does each person get?

1108
01:12:27,473 --> 01:12:27,786
Uh'?

1109
01:12:29,231 --> 01:12:29,904
Hum...?

1110
01:12:30,567 --> 01:12:35,969
And so, it's one, two, three, four, five, six...

1111
01:12:36,377 --> 01:12:38,978
One-sixth of an apple each.

1112
01:12:39,999 --> 01:12:43,209
Stop, stop, stop, stop. That's multiplying.

1113
01:12:43,313 --> 01:12:44,984
What? No way!

1114
01:12:45,216 --> 01:12:47,066
When you multiply it's more?

1115
01:12:47,131 --> 01:12:50,883
If you divided two-thirds of an apple by a quarter...

1116
01:12:55,097 --> 01:12:56,264
Anyhoo!

1117
01:12:57,824 --> 01:12:59,771
Stop thinking of the apples,

1118
01:13:00,271 --> 01:13:01,333
all you have to remember

1119
01:13:01,786 --> 01:13:02,989
to multiply you leave it the same.

1120
01:13:03,122 --> 01:13:04,231
To divide you reverse it.

1121
01:13:13,132 --> 01:13:15,171
Is that actress in Takarazuka?

1122
01:13:15,352 --> 01:13:16,382
S.K.D.

1123
01:13:17,547 --> 01:13:19,398
A "D" in her math exam.

1124
01:13:20,421 --> 01:13:21,009
A "D"?

1125
01:13:21,372 --> 01:13:23,812
That's right and it's better than last time.

1126
01:13:26,447 --> 01:13:30,210
If she got a "B" or a "C" I could tell her to work harder.

1127
01:13:30,400 --> 01:13:31,468
Yeah you could.

1128
01:13:32,741 --> 01:13:35,452
Should you maybe get her IQ tested?

1129
01:13:35,815 --> 01:13:38,765
When she first started school she did pretty well.

1130
01:13:38,844 --> 01:13:40,198
She's getting dumber.

1131
01:13:40,413 --> 01:13:43,265
She did fall down the stairs when she was a baby.

1132
01:13:43,530 --> 01:13:45,812
That's right, in her baby walker.

1133
01:13:46,326 --> 01:13:48,335
I really thought she was dead for sure.

1134
01:13:48,897 --> 01:13:50,671
All she got was a bump on the head.

1135
01:13:50,687 --> 01:13:52,076
And now it's affecting her.

1136
01:13:52,092 --> 01:13:54,060
Your right. That must be it!

1137
01:13:54,265 --> 01:13:57,894
I don't think that's it. She's just not very good at math.

1138
01:13:57,896 --> 01:13:59,882
I bet shes talking all the time in class.

1139
01:13:59,998 --> 01:14:02,858
If she'd just listen, divisional fractions would be easy.

1140
01:14:03,187 --> 01:14:04,780
Any idiot can do it.

1141
01:14:04,818 --> 01:14:07,827
And what about next year, shes going into sixth grade.

1142
01:14:07,902 --> 01:14:09,456
I never see her studying at home.

1143
01:14:09,580 --> 01:14:10,385
That's true.

1144
01:14:10,640 --> 01:14:12,093
I don't get it.

1145
01:14:12,292 --> 01:14:16,369
Dividing two-thirds of an apple, by one-forth of an apple.

1146
01:14:16,385 --> 01:14:19,749
I haven't the slightest idea what that could possibly be.

1147
01:14:20,199 --> 01:14:21,687
I'll show them.

1148
01:14:22,257 --> 01:14:24,363
Divided two-thirds of an apple

1149
01:14:24,379 --> 01:14:25,919
by a quarter means...

1150
01:14:26,650 --> 01:14:29,512
Ahh! I don't get it!

1151
01:14:32,428 --> 01:14:34,117
I never came to grips with it.

1152
01:14:34,210 --> 01:14:36,061
Have you ever felt that way about anything?

1153
01:14:36,443 --> 01:14:37,579
Even a fraction?

1154
01:14:38,903 --> 01:14:39,757
Hum...

1155
01:14:43,403 --> 01:14:44,116
You know what?

1156
01:14:44,944 --> 01:14:47,799
We have to work even harder on organic farming.

1157
01:14:48,007 --> 01:14:50,815
We've let the rich and powerful
take control of us farmers.

1158
01:14:50,831 --> 01:14:52,796
We've tried to be like people from the city.

1159
01:14:53,358 --> 01:14:54,965
But lost ourselves along the way.

1160
01:14:54,981 --> 01:14:58,619
So, we have to think, about
getting back to real aquaculture.

1161
01:14:58,635 --> 01:14:59,530
As it was.

1162
01:15:01,561 --> 01:15:02,577
Goodness me...

1163
01:15:05,203 --> 01:15:07,522
Farming, it's really a passion.

1164
01:15:08,478 --> 01:15:08,874
Mm.

1165
01:15:12,134 --> 01:15:14,343
You know... That's my friends speech.

1166
01:15:15,770 --> 01:15:18,085
Yup', but I feel the same way.

1167
01:15:18,887 --> 01:15:23,594
I think it's great... the... all the thought you put
into division of fractions is still so important to you.

1168
01:15:23,736 --> 01:15:26,218
Well, I didn't mean it to sound like a big deal.

1169
01:15:28,283 --> 01:15:32,163
People are always telling me, that
I got a good job, at a good company

1170
01:15:32,874 --> 01:15:35,311
but its not something that I'm really into.

1171
01:15:35,835 --> 01:15:37,965
You clearly love farming.

1172
01:15:38,356 --> 01:15:41,819
Its difficult not to admire your conviction.

1173
01:15:43,840 --> 01:15:45,358
Are you.. Kidding?

1174
01:15:47,867 --> 01:15:48,984
Of course not!

1175
01:15:49,510 --> 01:15:52,023
Your lucky you know what you want from life.

1176
01:15:58,179 --> 01:16:00,131
Agra culture is a declining industry.

1177
01:16:00,498 --> 01:16:03,539
It'll be nice if we're in a situation
where we could just work through it

1178
01:16:03,948 --> 01:16:06,046
and not have to think about it but... We're not.

1179
01:16:06,134 --> 01:16:08,375
So... we've got a lot to think about.

1180
01:16:08,914 --> 01:16:11,327
We've got to learn from each other. Back each other up.

1181
01:16:11,343 --> 01:16:12,914
If we don't, we'll never make it.

1182
01:16:19,742 --> 01:16:21,296
Taeko do you ski?

1183
01:16:21,563 --> 01:16:22,269
Yeah.

1184
01:16:22,470 --> 01:16:25,353
I've been a couple times with
some friends but I'm not very good.

1185
01:16:25,369 --> 01:16:25,836
Great.

1186
01:16:26,184 --> 01:16:27,319
Hey, you know what...

1187
01:16:27,344 --> 01:16:29,328
Why don't you come back and ski this winter?

1188
01:16:29,838 --> 01:16:32,320
Wait. You're really good at it aren't you?

1189
01:16:33,055 --> 01:16:36,855
I.. I'm all right. I'm an
instructor here at Zaō in the winter.

1190
01:16:36,933 --> 01:16:40,354
An instructor? You must be great.

1191
01:16:40,999 --> 01:16:43,414
Naw, every one around here is an instructor.

1192
01:17:05,561 --> 01:17:07,561
Now this is countryside.

1193
01:17:08,076 --> 01:17:09,623
The real countryside.

1194
01:17:10,169 --> 01:17:11,154
Not like Zao.

1195
01:17:13,108 --> 01:17:15,115
Um... Not really.

1196
01:17:15,225 --> 01:17:17,975
Oh, Zaō was beautiful but...

1197
01:17:18,074 --> 01:17:20,967
Don't worry. It's interesting you say that.

1198
01:17:21,467 --> 01:17:22,038
Oh?

1199
01:17:22,318 --> 01:17:22,787
Mmm.

1200
01:17:23,360 --> 01:17:27,248
City people see forest and woods
and streams and they're happy.

1201
01:17:27,422 --> 01:17:29,686
Because they think what they see is "nature".

1202
01:17:30,787 --> 01:17:32,743
Apart from back deep in the mountains

1203
01:17:33,084 --> 01:17:36,092
almost every thing you see here is the work of a farmer.

1204
01:17:36,764 --> 01:17:37,600
That so?

1205
01:17:38,027 --> 01:17:39,506
Sure, of course it is.

1206
01:17:44,303 --> 01:17:45,217
The river?

1207
01:17:45,271 --> 01:17:46,006
A dam.

1208
01:17:46,479 --> 01:17:47,514
And those woods?

1209
01:17:47,645 --> 01:17:48,365
Planted.

1210
01:17:49,143 --> 01:17:50,154
And this stream?

1211
01:17:50,193 --> 01:17:50,678
Dug.

1212
01:17:51,670 --> 01:17:55,365
Irrigation, it's not just the paddies and the fields.

1213
01:17:55,838 --> 01:17:57,701
Everything has been touched by man.

1214
01:17:58,326 --> 01:18:01,397
Our ancestors cleared this and cultivated that

1215
01:18:01,811 --> 01:18:05,056
encouraged mushrooms, Berry's, wild garlic.

1216
01:18:05,072 --> 01:18:05,709
Really?

1217
01:18:05,935 --> 01:18:09,490
Yeah. The scenery come about by lucky accident.

1218
01:18:09,989 --> 01:18:14,193
As people have struggled with nature
to get what they needed to survive.

1219
01:18:14,858 --> 01:18:19,029
So without people, this scenery wouldn't have been here.

1220
01:18:19,771 --> 01:18:21,256
No it wouldn't have.

1221
01:18:22,108 --> 01:18:23,797
To get what they need from nature,

1222
01:18:24,115 --> 01:18:29,717
farmers have to do a lot of different things to
make sure that nature will continue to provide forever.

1223
01:18:34,139 --> 01:18:37,701
It's sort a joint venture between people and the earth.

1224
01:18:39,341 --> 01:18:41,272
That's how the country side works.

1225
01:18:42,564 --> 01:18:43,912
Now I get it.

1226
01:18:44,676 --> 01:18:46,342
All these feelings I have.

1227
01:18:47,538 --> 01:18:49,546
Almost nostalgic for this place.

1228
01:18:50,022 --> 01:18:52,639
There's a connection even though it's not where I grew up.

1229
01:18:53,149 --> 01:18:54,671
Does that make any sense?

1230
01:18:57,615 --> 01:18:59,374
So, that's what it is.

1231
01:19:49,071 --> 01:19:50,855
Oh my poor back.

1232
01:19:52,197 --> 01:19:55,699
I'm not sure what's so cool about organic farming?

1233
01:19:57,933 --> 01:20:00,744
I told you... It's very cool in theory but...

1234
01:20:01,311 --> 01:20:03,939
The difficult part is putting it all into practice.

1235
01:20:03,968 --> 01:20:05,883
Helping everything grow naturally.

1236
01:20:06,052 --> 01:20:09,369
Tell me again why we're farming
like it's a hundred years ago.

1237
01:20:09,606 --> 01:20:13,775
These days, with most of your organic
rice they'll spray it once with weed-killer.

1238
01:20:14,139 --> 01:20:16,590
Most places don't weed by hand like they used to.

1239
01:20:17,669 --> 01:20:19,267
There just isn't the manpower to do it.

1240
01:20:21,616 --> 01:20:23,205
You're really working hard aren't cha'?

1241
01:20:23,321 --> 01:20:24,400
Ya' ready for a break?

1242
01:20:25,533 --> 01:20:26,603
How about some tea?

1243
01:20:26,934 --> 01:20:28,838
Yes! I'd love some.

1244
01:20:29,778 --> 01:20:32,484
Anything to take a break from organic farming.

1245
01:20:40,127 --> 01:20:44,236
Thanks to Toshio, I got to
try a whole bunch of new things.

1246
01:20:44,720 --> 01:20:48,158
I was proud to learn about a
world I'd always felt close to

1247
01:20:48,681 --> 01:20:50,210
but never truly knew.

1248
01:21:19,828 --> 01:21:20,469
Wow.

1249
01:21:39,995 --> 01:21:42,832
"Oh, the crows are flying away."

1250
01:21:43,594 --> 01:21:44,238
"Look!"

1251
01:21:47,580 --> 01:21:50,076
I finely got to see that for real.

1252
01:21:54,246 --> 01:21:56,519
That was my most famous line ever.

1253
01:21:57,098 --> 01:21:59,574
I had just one line in my school play.

1254
01:22:00,879 --> 01:22:01,550
Really?

1255
01:22:03,121 --> 01:22:04,388
Yeah, me too.

1256
01:22:04,605 --> 01:22:06,269
I only got small parts to play.

1257
01:22:06,501 --> 01:22:07,394
How 'bout you?

1258
01:22:08,170 --> 01:22:10,686
Hmm... I always get the big parts.

1259
01:22:11,064 --> 01:22:13,311
Cause there aren't very many kids in my class.

1260
01:22:13,673 --> 01:22:14,467
That's great..

1261
01:22:15,365 --> 01:22:16,498
But on the other hand,

1262
01:22:16,679 --> 01:22:18,299
it's a bit of a problem here.

1263
01:22:18,315 --> 01:22:22,898
You can't imagine how modern farming
has forced family's to the city for work.

1264
01:22:22,900 --> 01:22:24,373
So, not many kids around, huh?

1265
01:22:24,388 --> 01:22:25,177
Yeah.

1266
01:22:25,369 --> 01:22:27,654
Hey, at least it makes drama more fun.

1267
01:22:28,141 --> 01:22:30,771
Mmm, nuh-uh, I'm more into sports.

1268
01:22:31,107 --> 01:22:32,021
I like track and field.

1269
01:22:32,056 --> 01:22:33,189
I'm a pretty good runner.

1270
01:22:34,200 --> 01:22:37,197
Are you? I was never more than average.

1271
01:22:37,670 --> 01:22:40,623
And no more than "Village Child 1:" On the school play.

1272
01:22:40,887 --> 01:22:44,826
But you know what? I'll never ever forget that one line.

1273
01:22:45,311 --> 01:22:49,694
It's crazy... I honestly thought
I was going to become a star.

1274
01:22:50,092 --> 01:22:50,951
A star?

1275
01:22:51,207 --> 01:22:51,701
Yup'.

1276
01:22:52,519 --> 01:22:53,191
Really?

1277
01:22:53,559 --> 01:22:55,060
As "Village Child 1?"

1278
01:22:55,305 --> 01:22:55,886
Sure.

1279
01:22:56,965 --> 01:22:59,159
Like... You were going to move to Holly wood?

1280
01:22:59,381 --> 01:23:00,152
I know.

1281
01:23:01,089 --> 01:23:02,917
I really threw my self into the part.

1282
01:23:04,239 --> 01:23:06,072
I bet you were adorable back then.

1283
01:23:06,583 --> 01:23:08,089
No, it's not that!

1284
01:23:08,941 --> 01:23:11,908
I would practice in front of
the mirror for hours and hours.

1285
01:23:12,425 --> 01:23:13,386
You did what?

1286
01:23:14,050 --> 01:23:15,253
For "Village Child 1"...

1287
01:23:15,269 --> 01:23:16,605
I practiced.

1288
01:23:16,848 --> 01:23:18,859
You see I only had one line

1289
01:23:19,055 --> 01:23:20,792
and I couldn't do very much with it.

1290
01:23:21,269 --> 01:23:25,005
"Aw, the crows are flying away... look."

1291
01:23:25,277 --> 01:23:26,097
Tricky huh?

1292
01:23:26,595 --> 01:23:29,096
And then, I bet, you invented new lines.

1293
01:23:29,487 --> 01:23:30,558
Of course.

1294
01:23:32,338 --> 01:23:37,800
Aw... Look up there, all the crows are flying away today.

1295
01:23:39,003 --> 01:23:40,762
Watch them fly away.

1296
01:23:41,006 --> 01:23:41,906
There's two.

1297
01:23:41,908 --> 01:23:42,816
There's three...

1298
01:23:42,892 --> 01:23:43,923
There's four...

1299
01:23:45,562 --> 01:23:49,097
See you later. Goodbye crows.

1300
01:23:51,042 --> 01:23:52,300
Bye.

1301
01:23:52,752 --> 01:23:54,066
And the teacher loved it.

1302
01:23:54,265 --> 01:23:55,589
Not one bit.

1303
01:23:56,192 --> 01:23:58,355
Fine that was very nice.

1304
01:23:59,004 --> 01:24:03,341
But please, lets only say the
lines that are written on the script.

1305
01:24:07,297 --> 01:24:10,816
We are the magicians of the village.

1306
01:24:11,033 --> 01:24:14,506
We will put a spell on you.

1307
01:24:15,503 --> 01:24:18,086
That's sad, what's wrong with a few extra words.

1308
01:24:18,102 --> 01:24:20,836
They weren't very good anyways
so I didn't mind giving them up.

1309
01:24:21,014 --> 01:24:23,735
But I still had the desire to express myself.

1310
01:24:24,094 --> 01:24:26,574
I realized what I couldn't do with words

1311
01:24:26,716 --> 01:24:29,125
I could express in the way I moved.

1312
01:24:32,514 --> 01:24:34,074
Aah...

1313
01:24:35,923 --> 01:24:39,168
Oh look, the crows are flying away.

1314
01:24:44,290 --> 01:24:45,285
There.

1315
01:24:45,300 --> 01:24:46,308
There's two.

1316
01:24:46,516 --> 01:24:47,621
There's three.

1317
01:24:47,636 --> 01:24:48,726
There's four.

1318
01:25:02,863 --> 01:25:04,187
Bye.

1319
01:25:10,449 --> 01:25:11,636
That all it was.

1320
01:25:13,292 --> 01:25:14,714
But it was worth the effort.

1321
01:25:15,144 --> 01:25:17,339
"Village Child 1" was a big hit.

1322
01:25:18,073 --> 01:25:19,362
It's hard to believe, right?

1323
01:25:20,463 --> 01:25:23,697
All the teachers said I was
truly fantastic n' stole the show.

1324
01:25:23,862 --> 01:25:26,338
And I was asked to join a local theater company.

1325
01:25:27,385 --> 01:25:30,322
Then one day, it got even better than that.

1326
01:25:34,149 --> 01:25:35,385
Hello, excuse me?

1327
01:25:35,400 --> 01:25:35,744
Oh!

1328
01:25:35,846 --> 01:25:36,588
Coming.

1329
01:25:36,777 --> 01:25:39,814
Then suddenly several dozen sticks of dynamite went off.

1330
01:25:39,971 --> 01:25:41,541
Boom! Right in front of me.

1331
01:25:41,675 --> 01:25:43,624
In front of you.

1332
01:25:44,322 --> 01:25:45,755
Really, Taeko?

1333
01:25:45,771 --> 01:25:47,521
...with granny and captain kid.

1334
01:25:47,523 --> 01:25:50,642
And all the potatoes turned out to be dynamite.

1335
01:25:50,658 --> 01:25:53,158
Our physical play has a child roll.

1336
01:25:57,595 --> 01:26:02,468
We'd very much like your daughter Taeko, to
perform in the university theater production.

1337
01:26:02,470 --> 01:26:03,676
We think she'd be fantastic.

1338
01:26:03,678 --> 01:26:04,730
Perform!

1339
01:26:04,791 --> 01:26:05,541
I see.

1340
01:26:06,057 --> 01:26:08,873
We'd have rehearsal on Saturday afternoons.

1341
01:26:09,164 --> 01:26:11,509
And I promise they wouldn't go too late.

1342
01:26:11,822 --> 01:26:13,830
Alright, but...

1343
01:26:14,899 --> 01:26:18,143
Oh and we'll make sure she gets home okay.

1344
01:26:18,652 --> 01:26:20,499
Me in a grown-up play?

1345
01:26:20,697 --> 01:26:22,869
Not with those amateur kids.

1346
01:26:22,977 --> 01:26:25,314
I'll be with real grown-ups!

1347
01:26:25,377 --> 01:26:27,154
I'll be a star!

1348
01:26:28,372 --> 01:26:35,878
Oh, oh, oh, oh what a wonderful day.

1349
01:26:36,109 --> 01:26:37,797
Cock-a Cock-a Cock-a Cock-a.

1350
01:26:37,944 --> 01:26:39,061
Cock-a.

1351
01:26:39,098 --> 01:26:41,259
Cock-a Cock-a Cock-a Cock-a.

1352
01:26:41,261 --> 01:26:42,244
'Gack'-a.

1353
01:26:42,556 --> 01:26:44,536
Cock-a Cock-a Cock-a Cock-a.

1354
01:26:44,538 --> 01:26:45,747
'Gack'-a.

1355
01:26:45,774 --> 01:26:47,773
Cock-a Cock-a Cock-a Cock-a.

1356
01:26:47,775 --> 01:26:49,481
'Gack'-a.

1357
01:26:54,403 --> 01:26:55,886
Oh! Mom!

1358
01:26:58,045 --> 01:26:58,983
Who was that?

1359
01:26:59,307 --> 01:27:03,337
A young man from Nihon University
wants you to be in his production.

1360
01:27:03,499 --> 01:27:06,827
Taeko, I guess you did really well in the school play.

1361
01:27:07,287 --> 01:27:08,704
And? So?

1362
01:27:09,225 --> 01:27:13,929
He said that he'd hoped you do
it and he ask me very respectfully.

1363
01:27:21,093 --> 01:27:22,918
Hey, that's great!

1364
01:27:23,304 --> 01:27:25,347
So, you finally you found something your good at.

1365
01:27:25,479 --> 01:27:28,401
No, no Taeko wrights some very good essays.

1366
01:27:28,426 --> 01:27:31,081
Sounds like she's perfectly suited for this.

1367
01:27:31,203 --> 01:27:32,979
Much better than studying math.

1368
01:27:33,856 --> 01:27:35,284
Oh yeah. For sure.

1369
01:27:35,539 --> 01:27:38,402
You know, I played the lead part "Tongue-Cut Sparrow"

1370
01:27:38,418 --> 01:27:40,589
but nobody ask me to be in their play.

1371
01:27:41,260 --> 01:27:42,684
I know, I know!

1372
01:27:43,313 --> 01:27:45,221
So... What's next?

1373
01:28:08,839 --> 01:28:11,803
This is show business. You could become a child star.

1374
01:28:11,819 --> 01:28:12,519
Huh?

1375
01:28:13,012 --> 01:28:14,855
You should join the Takarazuka.

1376
01:28:15,132 --> 01:28:18,088
Yes! If you practice, maybe you could join them.

1377
01:28:19,924 --> 01:28:21,398
We'll have no performing.

1378
01:28:21,414 --> 01:28:22,010
Huh?

1379
01:28:23,120 --> 01:28:24,498
No show business.

1380
01:28:26,410 --> 01:28:29,356
Dad... its university play, not real show biz.

1381
01:28:29,372 --> 01:28:31,212
That's right. It's just...

1382
01:28:32,082 --> 01:28:32,868
I said no.

1383
01:28:34,305 --> 01:28:34,962
My dinner.

1384
01:28:35,947 --> 01:28:36,587
Yes.

1385
01:28:55,268 --> 01:28:57,637
Dad can get really stubborn, can't he.

1386
01:28:57,896 --> 01:29:01,649
This is your fault. Your the one
that said I could become a child star.

1387
01:29:01,958 --> 01:29:03,508
Can I get in the bath first?

1388
01:29:03,816 --> 01:29:04,614
Sure you can.

1389
01:29:06,277 --> 01:29:07,911
And Takarazuka.

1390
01:29:08,851 --> 01:29:10,965
All that stuff about show business.

1391
01:29:12,031 --> 01:29:13,903
Why'd you have to tell him that, huh?

1392
01:29:14,189 --> 01:29:15,340
Why Nanako?

1393
01:29:16,973 --> 01:29:18,145
Your such a pest.

1394
01:29:23,219 --> 01:29:32,853
Poor boy, poor boy, don't you feel sorry for me?

1395
01:29:33,313 --> 01:29:35,774
I promise, we won't take much of her time.

1396
01:29:36,316 --> 01:29:38,415
Yes, but I-I-I...

1397
01:29:39,626 --> 01:29:41,415
We'd very much appreciate it.

1398
01:29:42,118 --> 01:29:44,079
She's really very shy...

1399
01:29:44,381 --> 01:29:45,391
Very timid.

1400
01:29:52,707 --> 01:29:55,625
I realise you had to come all the way here again

1401
01:29:55,733 --> 01:29:57,442
I'm really very sorry.

1402
01:29:57,755 --> 01:30:02,675
Poor boy, poor boy...

1403
01:30:02,927 --> 01:30:07,347
Such a long way from home...

1404
01:30:08,224 --> 01:30:18,264
Poor boy.

1405
01:30:22,647 --> 01:30:26,637
And now Aoki from class 5-1 is going to act in that play.

1406
01:30:30,455 --> 01:30:33,152
She's been going around telling everyone.

1407
01:30:33,824 --> 01:30:34,613
Oh?

1408
01:30:34,799 --> 01:30:36,831
Today, her mother even came to the school

1409
01:30:36,873 --> 01:30:41,506
and Aoki got to change into her
best clothes to go to Nihon University.

1410
01:30:41,565 --> 01:30:45,446
Her dress had enormous frills that go all the way out.

1411
01:30:45,609 --> 01:30:46,449
Taeko.

1412
01:30:46,542 --> 01:30:46,996
Huh?

1413
01:30:47,807 --> 01:30:53,198
You can't tell anyone that the young man from
Nihon University came and asked for you first.

1414
01:30:55,420 --> 01:30:59,808
How do you think the other girl would feel
knowing that she wasn't their first choice.

1415
01:31:04,469 --> 01:31:05,511
Understood?

1416
01:31:09,019 --> 01:31:09,928
Well Taeko?

1417
01:31:11,595 --> 01:31:12,385
Hmm.

1418
01:31:28,490 --> 01:31:30,045
That was news for children.

1419
01:31:30,047 --> 01:31:33,693
And now its time for pop-up pumpkin island.

1420
01:31:40,456 --> 01:31:43,771
Breaking through the waves.

1421
01:31:45,616 --> 01:31:48,702
Shooting through the clouds.

1422
01:31:50,613 --> 01:32:00,369
Where is it heading? Yokkori
Pumpkin island? Where will it take us?

1423
01:32:01,416 --> 01:32:06,773
Something special waits for us,

1424
01:32:06,920 --> 01:32:11,507
Just over the horizon.

1425
01:32:11,894 --> 01:32:17,023
There'll be hard times, there'll be sad times,

1426
01:32:17,232 --> 01:32:19,579
but we'll never lose heart.

1427
01:32:19,735 --> 01:32:21,944
We hate to cry, so let's laugh instead.

1428
01:32:22,160 --> 01:32:25,079
Let's go!

1429
01:32:25,240 --> 01:32:27,550
Hyokkori Pumpkin island!

1430
01:32:27,860 --> 01:32:30,284
Hyokkori Pumpkin island!

1431
01:32:30,559 --> 01:32:36,289
Hyokkori Pumpkin island!

1432
01:32:48,287 --> 01:32:50,699
So sad. Poor little Taeko.

1433
01:32:53,224 --> 01:32:56,586
I guess I never really managed
to put all all that behind me.

1434
01:32:57,403 --> 01:33:01,156
So, as soon as I got to high school,
I immediately joined the drama club.

1435
01:33:02,216 --> 01:33:02,859
And then what?

1436
01:33:03,695 --> 01:33:06,706
Turns out "Village Child 1" was a bit of a "one-off".

1437
01:33:06,731 --> 01:33:07,317
Really?

1438
01:33:08,449 --> 01:33:09,968
I wasn't gonna be a star.

1439
01:33:10,980 --> 01:33:12,994
But I had a lot of fun and well ah...

1440
01:33:13,514 --> 01:33:14,736
Ah to much. It was just a dream.

1441
01:33:15,633 --> 01:33:16,602
Yeah, but...

1442
01:33:18,965 --> 01:33:23,051
Your old man, your old man. Whether
it's in Tokyo or out here in the country.

1443
01:33:24,822 --> 01:33:29,215
You know, when I was in high school,
all I wanted to do was to go to Tokyo.

1444
01:33:33,028 --> 01:33:35,645
I wanted to apply to a couples of colleges there but...

1445
01:33:35,945 --> 01:33:37,100
It didn't come to anything.

1446
01:33:38,631 --> 01:33:39,981
Must have been frustrating.

1447
01:33:41,653 --> 01:33:42,583
I accepted it

1448
01:33:42,992 --> 01:33:45,036
but some of those guys who went to Tokyo

1449
01:33:45,161 --> 01:33:48,479
they were no smarter when they
came back than when they went away.

1450
01:33:50,262 --> 01:33:51,354
Doesn't bother me now.

1451
01:33:51,606 --> 01:33:53,685
My father always knew I would make a good farmer.

1452
01:33:54,054 --> 01:33:55,606
The old mans pretty wise.

1453
01:33:58,485 --> 01:34:00,567
I think I know how you must have felt.

1454
01:34:01,278 --> 01:34:04,317
Oh! But I was never really going
to be an actor, don't you see.

1455
01:34:04,319 --> 01:34:06,388
Course I do. But it's the same thing.

1456
01:34:09,345 --> 01:34:11,864
"I am happy as my face shows."

1457
01:34:12,107 --> 01:34:14,837
"My face shows that I don't care."

1458
01:34:16,460 --> 01:34:18,063
I love that program as well.

1459
01:34:18,298 --> 01:34:19,118
You did?

1460
01:34:19,796 --> 01:34:21,899
Machine Gun Dandy he was great.

1461
01:34:21,966 --> 01:34:23,899
I had such a crush on him!

1462
01:34:24,870 --> 01:34:25,818
'Can believe that.

1463
01:34:26,043 --> 01:34:28,386
Hey, there were a lot of uplifting songs on that show.

1464
01:34:28,435 --> 01:34:29,561
Do you remember any of them?

1465
01:34:30,237 --> 01:34:32,579
Wait, how did that other one go? Ah!

1466
01:34:32,768 --> 01:34:35,074
"If today's is bad then tomorrow will be better."

1467
01:34:35,076 --> 01:34:37,508
"And if tomorrow is bad then try a little harder."

1468
01:34:37,674 --> 01:34:40,334
"You will see and you will know."

1469
01:34:40,484 --> 01:34:42,469
"Tomorrow tomorrow."

1470
01:34:42,690 --> 01:34:45,324
Don Don Gabacho. Don Gabacho.

1471
01:34:48,846 --> 01:34:49,924
Your crazy!

1472
01:34:50,619 --> 01:34:53,307
"If today's is bad then tomorrow will be better."

1473
01:34:53,424 --> 01:34:56,383
"And if tomorrow is bad then try a little harder."

1474
01:34:57,182 --> 01:35:00,893
The song Toshio recalled, reminds me to always look ahead.

1475
01:35:01,323 --> 01:35:02,801
That there's always tomorrow.

1476
01:35:03,264 --> 01:35:04,252
I love that.

1477
01:35:05,320 --> 01:35:07,736
Of course... Tomorrow.

1478
01:35:20,456 --> 01:35:22,366
So, your leaving tomorrow.

1479
01:35:22,838 --> 01:35:23,598
Yes.

1480
01:35:24,623 --> 01:35:27,016
Thank you for all that you've done for me this summer.

1481
01:35:27,957 --> 01:35:29,594
May you stay well granny.

1482
01:35:29,904 --> 01:35:31,239
Thank you Taeko.

1483
01:35:37,919 --> 01:35:41,463
My dear, do you like this place?

1484
01:35:41,568 --> 01:35:42,839
Yes, I love it.

1485
01:35:43,398 --> 01:35:45,702
I always feel very much at home here.

1486
01:35:46,041 --> 01:35:47,141
Well, I'm glad.

1487
01:35:47,904 --> 01:35:49,280
I was born here.

1488
01:35:49,881 --> 01:35:52,060
It's the only place I've ever called home.

1489
01:35:52,062 --> 01:35:53,568
I've never left.

1490
01:35:53,630 --> 01:35:56,853
Well, I did go to Tokyo, on one occasion.

1491
01:35:56,997 --> 01:35:59,318
When Arimitsuo married your sister

1492
01:35:59,411 --> 01:36:01,239
I much prefer it here.

1493
01:36:01,255 --> 01:36:02,372
Do you my dear?

1494
01:36:02,644 --> 01:36:04,396
Yeah... Actually I do.

1495
01:36:05,012 --> 01:36:07,380
Tokyo is always such a tangle of traffic.

1496
01:36:07,775 --> 01:36:10,279
Even on a hot day it can be a cold place to live.

1497
01:36:10,632 --> 01:36:13,529
Out in the countryside nature connects people.

1498
01:36:14,098 --> 01:36:18,193
Taeko, could you ever see
yourself living in a place like this?

1499
01:36:18,523 --> 01:36:20,346
Sure, I suppose I could.

1500
01:36:21,013 --> 01:36:22,811
Everyone around here is so nice.

1501
01:36:26,401 --> 01:36:27,099
Taeko.

1502
01:36:28,780 --> 01:36:32,402
I was thinking, why don't you become Toshio wife?

1503
01:36:33,739 --> 01:36:34,310
Huh?

1504
01:36:35,021 --> 01:36:38,224
Mitsuo left for the city when he met Nanako

1505
01:36:38,802 --> 01:36:41,255
but if you like it here you could stay.

1506
01:36:41,325 --> 01:36:42,677
No need to leave.

1507
01:36:42,740 --> 01:36:44,458
Stay and marry Toshio.

1508
01:36:44,493 --> 01:36:45,841
You'd be happy.

1509
01:36:46,508 --> 01:36:47,255
Granny!

1510
01:36:47,650 --> 01:36:50,513
Mother... Now where did that come from?

1511
01:36:51,270 --> 01:36:52,833
You'll scare the poor girl.

1512
01:36:53,554 --> 01:36:55,802
Will you consider it Taeko.

1513
01:36:57,213 --> 01:37:00,138
Don't take her seriously. You
know what a big kidder she is.

1514
01:37:00,370 --> 01:37:02,390
Mom, stop messing around.

1515
01:37:02,392 --> 01:37:04,819
I am not messing around.

1516
01:37:05,142 --> 01:37:07,727
I know that you'd like her to stay as well.

1517
01:37:08,107 --> 01:37:09,349
Er, mother...

1518
01:37:09,865 --> 01:37:11,968
It's not about what we'd like and what we'd wouldn't...

1519
01:37:11,984 --> 01:37:14,872
We'd love her to stay. Of course we would.

1520
01:37:15,200 --> 01:37:19,302
But we know that girls from the
city are much more independent.

1521
01:37:19,318 --> 01:37:20,516
We can't assume that.

1522
01:37:20,802 --> 01:37:21,603
Exactly.

1523
01:37:21,927 --> 01:37:26,033
But you know, she does seem to like it here.

1524
01:37:26,520 --> 01:37:28,056
And she's a good worker.

1525
01:37:28,614 --> 01:37:30,806
It does my heart good to see it.

1526
01:37:31,369 --> 01:37:34,542
I'd like nothing better that
to see her end up with Toshio.

1527
01:37:34,558 --> 01:37:36,531
Now Kiyoko... Don't you start too.

1528
01:37:36,533 --> 01:37:38,431
Your embarrassing the poor girl.

1529
01:37:39,736 --> 01:37:42,900
Taeko's got a good job with a good company in Tokyo.

1530
01:37:43,322 --> 01:37:45,052
And Toshio younger than her.

1531
01:37:45,068 --> 01:37:45,869
What?!?

1532
01:37:46,392 --> 01:37:48,767
What's that got to do with anything.

1533
01:37:50,650 --> 01:37:53,556
Taeko... Don't listen to him.

1534
01:37:54,252 --> 01:37:55,884
You could work in Yamagata.

1535
01:37:56,072 --> 01:37:58,756
Or y-you could stay here and work on the farm.

1536
01:37:58,772 --> 01:38:01,806
Kiyoko, now you shouldn't join in with this kind of talk.

1537
01:38:02,470 --> 01:38:04,728
Taeko came here for a nice vacation.

1538
01:38:05,312 --> 01:38:06,775
She's our guest here.

1539
01:38:07,719 --> 01:38:09,939
You are making her feel awkward.

1540
01:38:10,384 --> 01:38:12,221
I know you're not against it?

1541
01:38:12,332 --> 01:38:14,275
I against interfering all right.

1542
01:38:14,601 --> 01:38:16,955
I just think we need to be realistic.

1543
01:38:17,233 --> 01:38:21,420
For one thing I wonder if granny's
even bothered to speak to Toshio.

1544
01:38:21,489 --> 01:38:24,541
You can tell with one look what Toshio thinks.

1545
01:38:24,694 --> 01:38:25,712
Darn right.

1546
01:38:26,464 --> 01:38:28,920
It's not for you to say whether it could work.

1547
01:38:29,006 --> 01:38:30,433
Why don't we ask Taeko.

1548
01:38:31,354 --> 01:38:32,127
Taeko!

1549
01:38:38,401 --> 01:38:39,617
Just leave her be.

1550
01:38:40,941 --> 01:38:41,164
Tisk.

1551
01:38:42,586 --> 01:38:43,475
You see that.

1552
01:38:43,937 --> 01:38:44,703
She's gone.

1553
01:38:45,328 --> 01:38:47,101
You can't force these things.

1554
01:38:47,820 --> 01:38:50,522
I was only speaking my mind and being honest.

1555
01:39:05,762 --> 01:39:09,658
Marrying a farmer, I'd never once thought of that.

1556
01:39:10,253 --> 01:39:13,792
It's a strange feeling to even
imagine that kind of life could be mine,

1557
01:39:15,769 --> 01:39:18,676
it would have been so nice just to
be able to come right out and say,

1558
01:39:18,692 --> 01:39:21,636
"Sure, if he'll have me." Like
I'd seen in a movie somewhere.

1559
01:39:22,566 --> 01:39:24,410
But I couldn't bring myself to say it.

1560
01:39:25,855 --> 01:39:29,923
Now my shallow love of the country
side, my "Lets play farm." Childs game.

1561
01:39:30,418 --> 01:39:32,416
It all left me feeling guilty.

1562
01:39:34,120 --> 01:39:37,792
I'm mortified to think of how I
prattled on about how pleasant it is here.

1563
01:39:38,251 --> 01:39:39,146
How charming.

1564
01:39:39,699 --> 01:39:40,660
How ideal.

1565
01:39:41,441 --> 01:39:43,480
I've never struggled with a harsh winter.

1566
01:39:43,949 --> 01:39:44,816
Nor a blight.

1567
01:39:45,170 --> 01:39:46,988
Nor any reality of farming.

1568
01:39:47,739 --> 01:39:49,404
I can't do this.

1569
01:39:50,391 --> 01:39:51,806
I feel so foolish.

1570
01:39:52,511 --> 01:39:54,298
Living here the earth would swallow me up.

1571
01:40:03,237 --> 01:40:04,800
I'm not shaking hands with you.

1572
01:40:08,132 --> 01:40:10,826
Hey, did you see the shirt Abe wearing today.

1573
01:40:10,842 --> 01:40:11,608
Where?

1574
01:40:11,772 --> 01:40:14,194
Its the same shirt Tanaka had in the forth grade.

1575
01:40:14,444 --> 01:40:14,874
What?

1576
01:40:15,260 --> 01:40:16,030
Its a secret.

1577
01:40:16,571 --> 01:40:20,694
When it was his turn to feed the class
ducks, he kept the bread and took it home.

1578
01:40:21,046 --> 01:40:21,944
He did?

1579
01:40:22,186 --> 01:40:25,228
Have you seen the palms of his hands. They're filthy.

1580
01:40:25,772 --> 01:40:27,975
I'm sure glad I don't have to sit next to him.

1581
01:40:28,240 --> 01:40:29,826
Yeah, poor Taeko.

1582
01:40:30,034 --> 01:40:32,710
Go talk to the teacher and get your seat changed.

1583
01:40:33,124 --> 01:40:35,586
Yeah, he should sit next to another boy.

1584
01:40:35,695 --> 01:40:36,647
Right Taeko?

1585
01:40:37,991 --> 01:40:38,725
Well I...

1586
01:40:39,225 --> 01:40:40,916
I'm OK with him.

1587
01:40:41,183 --> 01:40:44,038
If I moved, I think it would hurt Abe feelings..

1588
01:40:44,100 --> 01:40:45,178
I would move.

1589
01:40:45,419 --> 01:40:47,046
Little Miss Goody Two Shoes.

1590
01:40:47,600 --> 01:40:50,647
Don't you dare tell him. Don't
tell him what we said to you.

1591
01:40:55,447 --> 01:40:56,709
I won't shake your hand.

1592
01:41:04,155 --> 01:41:05,114
Abe wait!

1593
01:41:18,354 --> 01:41:20,023
Taeko? What are you doing out here?

1594
01:41:20,385 --> 01:41:22,039
Oh, it's nothing.

1595
01:41:22,984 --> 01:41:24,180
I just needed some air.

1596
01:41:25,031 --> 01:41:26,305
Look at you. Your soaked.

1597
01:41:26,705 --> 01:41:29,711
Don't worry. C'mon, lets get in the car.

1598
01:41:45,249 --> 01:41:46,637
A little "going-away-gift".

1599
01:41:47,851 --> 01:41:48,989
My mother made it for you.

1600
01:41:50,947 --> 01:41:52,129
They're pickled onions.

1601
01:41:55,994 --> 01:41:58,400
Eh-no, please don't go back there.

1602
01:41:58,744 --> 01:41:59,892
Huh? Why not?

1603
01:42:00,356 --> 01:42:02,494
Please, just drive somewhere.

1604
01:42:03,860 --> 01:42:04,740
Are you okay?

1605
01:42:06,543 --> 01:42:10,599
I just saw someone. Like it was only yesterday.

1606
01:42:12,588 --> 01:42:13,365
Abe...

1607
01:42:14,735 --> 01:42:16,259
He was the new kid at school.

1608
01:42:18,396 --> 01:42:19,173
Looks the same.

1609
01:42:21,156 --> 01:42:23,084
I just saw him down the road.

1610
01:42:48,469 --> 01:42:49,974
So, this kid, Abe.

1611
01:42:50,810 --> 01:42:51,943
He was really poor.

1612
01:42:52,898 --> 01:42:54,279
He always wore the same thing.

1613
01:42:55,566 --> 01:42:56,513
He was filthy.

1614
01:42:57,138 --> 01:42:59,427
He was always snotty and always sickly.

1615
01:43:00,442 --> 01:43:02,174
He'd wipe his nose on his sleeve

1616
01:43:03,432 --> 01:43:05,448
and flick snot at us, oh!

1617
01:43:06,045 --> 01:43:08,776
And if you look at him even a little funny...

1618
01:43:10,987 --> 01:43:11,697
He'd say,

1619
01:43:11,797 --> 01:43:12,857
"What are you looking at."

1620
01:43:13,268 --> 01:43:15,848
"I'll knock those eyes out of
your head if you don't watch out."

1621
01:43:16,488 --> 01:43:17,979
I couldn't stand the little brat.

1622
01:43:20,100 --> 01:43:21,816
I had to sit next to him till summer,

1623
01:43:22,314 --> 01:43:23,785
and I couldn't swap my seat.

1624
01:43:24,980 --> 01:43:26,449
We did square dancing in the gym.

1625
01:43:26,660 --> 01:43:28,816
Even then I always seemed to wind up next to him.

1626
01:43:31,050 --> 01:43:35,096
He never did his homework and I hated
how he'd ask other people to copy theirs.

1627
01:43:35,270 --> 01:43:37,253
The other girls would gossip about him.

1628
01:43:38,638 --> 01:43:42,535
Ughh... I couldn't join in. I just wouldn't do that.

1629
01:43:43,589 --> 01:43:45,000
I knew that gossiping about him,

1630
01:43:45,166 --> 01:43:47,753
especially because I hated him,
it would be the worst thing ever.

1631
01:43:50,269 --> 01:43:50,953
But then...

1632
01:43:51,489 --> 01:43:55,277
Just before the summer vacation,
Abe was leaving for another school.

1633
01:43:57,659 --> 01:44:00,488
And the teacher decided that we
should each shake his hand, goodbye.

1634
01:44:00,985 --> 01:44:02,121
Nobody wanted to.

1635
01:44:03,918 --> 01:44:05,050
It was obvious.

1636
01:44:05,643 --> 01:44:07,089
So obvious.

1637
01:44:09,922 --> 01:44:11,253
He was really nervous

1638
01:44:12,167 --> 01:44:13,557
and his hands were dirty.

1639
01:44:16,216 --> 01:44:16,753
And so...

1640
01:44:17,735 --> 01:44:19,010
He went around to each kid...

1641
01:44:19,741 --> 01:44:20,690
N' shook their hand.

1642
01:44:21,942 --> 01:44:23,334
Every single kid.

1643
01:44:26,549 --> 01:44:28,182
Then he came back to his chair.

1644
01:44:28,989 --> 01:44:30,956
I was the last on to shake his hand.

1645
01:44:34,134 --> 01:44:36,235
I held it out and he said,

1646
01:44:37,523 --> 01:44:38,789
"I won't shake your hand."

1647
01:44:41,082 --> 01:44:42,760
"I'm not shaking hands with you."

1648
01:44:46,128 --> 01:44:47,718
"I not shaking hands with you."

1649
01:44:57,606 --> 01:44:59,753
I'm the one who thought the worst about him.

1650
01:45:02,536 --> 01:45:05,308
I feel like... Abe knew that.

1651
01:45:06,878 --> 01:45:08,690
That's why he wouldn't shake my hand.

1652
01:45:16,278 --> 01:45:18,403
Did something happened at Castawo's?

1653
01:45:19,643 --> 01:45:20,223
You see...

1654
01:45:22,198 --> 01:45:24,036
I was always a goody two-shoes.

1655
01:45:26,440 --> 01:45:27,582
I guess I still am.

1656
01:45:29,323 --> 01:45:30,273
Can't help it.

1657
01:45:42,134 --> 01:45:44,871
You're acting strange, really different today.

1658
01:45:48,339 --> 01:45:50,198
I don't know what they said to you at Castawo...

1659
01:45:50,374 --> 01:45:51,897
No, honestly no.

1660
01:45:52,368 --> 01:45:54,581
Nobody said anything at Castawo's.

1661
01:45:58,810 --> 01:45:59,631
I'm sorry.

1662
01:46:01,740 --> 01:46:04,178
I was just thinking back to when I was a kid

1663
01:46:04,952 --> 01:46:06,678
and feeling sorry for myself.

1664
01:46:09,584 --> 01:46:10,529
How 'bout this...

1665
01:46:12,320 --> 01:46:13,420
Maybe Abe...

1666
01:46:14,197 --> 01:46:16,486
Wouldn't shake your hand, because he liked you and

1667
01:46:16,785 --> 01:46:18,259
didn't want to say goodbye.

1668
01:46:20,751 --> 01:46:23,197
The girls he liked in class he would be nice to.

1669
01:46:23,830 --> 01:46:25,392
In front of me he acted all tough.

1670
01:46:26,681 --> 01:46:29,626
His hands jammed in pockets, using bad language,

1671
01:46:29,743 --> 01:46:32,009
swaggering around, spitting as he walked.

1672
01:46:34,375 --> 01:46:35,548
He was a little thug.

1673
01:46:36,329 --> 01:46:37,072
There you go.

1674
01:46:38,084 --> 01:46:39,580
It's just what boys do.

1675
01:46:40,631 --> 01:46:44,376
When I was little, I would tease the
girl I liked until she ran off home.

1676
01:46:44,508 --> 01:46:46,052
It's not the same Toshio.

1677
01:46:46,445 --> 01:46:49,415
I mean, he didn't skip anyone except for me.

1678
01:46:49,758 --> 01:46:51,081
I was the only one.

1679
01:46:51,083 --> 01:46:53,876
Well... Its like the saying goes. You know...

1680
01:46:55,210 --> 01:46:57,876
"Girls are always blind to the love of boys."

1681
01:46:58,225 --> 01:47:00,275
Huh. Do you really believe that?

1682
01:47:00,927 --> 01:47:02,392
Sure, it's obvious.

1683
01:47:04,273 --> 01:47:06,689
And it always has been so.

1684
01:47:08,290 --> 01:47:10,111
Abe wasn't really all that tough.

1685
01:47:10,412 --> 01:47:12,853
He couldn't act that way. Not with the boys.

1686
01:47:15,887 --> 01:47:18,191
I guess with you it was easy for him to act tough.

1687
01:47:18,279 --> 01:47:20,402
After all you sat right next to him in class.

1688
01:47:21,473 --> 01:47:23,691
He was taking advantage of the situation.

1689
01:47:24,402 --> 01:47:28,012
Hey, theirs no way he wanted to
shake hands with the whole class.

1690
01:47:28,375 --> 01:47:30,449
Your the only one he was honest about.

1691
01:47:31,116 --> 01:47:33,629
"I'm not shaking hands with you.", yea?

1692
01:47:57,864 --> 01:47:58,375
Ptui.

1693
01:47:59,498 --> 01:48:00,628
Knock it off huh.

1694
01:48:32,727 --> 01:48:33,086
Ptui.

1695
01:48:39,203 --> 01:48:39,560
Ptui.

1696
01:48:40,458 --> 01:48:40,811
Ptui.

1697
01:48:42,980 --> 01:48:43,242
Ptui.

1698
01:48:45,468 --> 01:48:45,779
Ptui.

1699
01:48:45,781 --> 01:48:50,101
I remember... I felt so bad for Abe and so guilty.

1700
01:48:51,555 --> 01:48:52,950
That I imitated him.

1701
01:48:55,899 --> 01:48:57,066
But it was too late.

1702
01:48:57,631 --> 01:48:58,856
The damage was done.

1703
01:48:59,433 --> 01:49:01,810
I couldn't undo what happened or my feelings of hate.

1704
01:49:01,826 --> 01:49:03,320
The fact is I hurt him.

1705
01:49:12,756 --> 01:49:15,072
Ah... Looks like it stopped raining.

1706
01:49:16,443 --> 01:49:17,373
That's nice.

1707
01:49:22,753 --> 01:49:23,824
Check out the moon.

1708
01:49:34,665 --> 01:49:37,884
Sometimes at night you can see tanuki and foxes out here.

1709
01:49:38,511 --> 01:49:39,110
Yeah?

1710
01:49:40,844 --> 01:49:41,836
Shall we get going?

1711
01:49:42,945 --> 01:49:45,892
Oh dear, they'll be worrying back at the house.

1712
01:49:49,667 --> 01:49:52,821
And... There'll be a few rumors
flying around, that's for sure.

1713
01:49:53,783 --> 01:49:56,790
I'm sorry, I've put you in an embarrassing position.

1714
01:49:58,060 --> 01:50:00,650
They sure wonder what happened at Castawo's today.

1715
01:50:00,870 --> 01:50:02,298
Don't ask them about it.

1716
01:50:02,472 --> 01:50:04,907
I'm serious. Promise me that you won't.

1717
01:50:09,331 --> 01:50:10,251
OK then,

1718
01:50:10,644 --> 01:50:11,673
a little music?

1719
01:50:50,632 --> 01:50:55,320
For the very first time, I'm thinking all
these things and feeling all these feelings.

1720
01:50:55,788 --> 01:50:57,617
Of my feelings towards Toshio,

1721
01:50:58,156 --> 01:51:00,093
of his feelings towards me.

1722
01:51:00,805 --> 01:51:05,203
Did I just open my confused head
and convoluted heart to this guy?

1723
01:51:05,943 --> 01:51:06,767
I did.

1724
01:51:07,655 --> 01:51:10,384
And yet, it was as easy as breathing in...

1725
01:51:11,743 --> 01:51:12,571
And breathing out.

1726
01:51:13,455 --> 01:51:16,837
I'm amazed at how I'd been
able to fall back on him that way.

1727
01:51:17,528 --> 01:51:18,665
I felt as if...

1728
01:51:19,195 --> 01:51:20,704
As if I'd always known him.

1729
01:51:22,014 --> 01:51:24,321
As if he was part of my own past.

1730
01:51:25,569 --> 01:51:28,040
And the one I wanted a hand shake from most was...

1731
01:51:28,574 --> 01:51:29,275
Toshio.

1732
01:51:31,916 --> 01:51:33,103
Just a hand shake.

1733
01:52:04,666 --> 01:52:05,833
What is this feeling?

1734
01:52:06,884 --> 01:52:09,161
Thinking about it with him so close to me.

1735
01:52:11,034 --> 01:52:11,864
I wonder?

1736
01:52:39,394 --> 01:52:41,053
Taeko, do you have everything?

1737
01:52:41,592 --> 01:52:43,120
Yes, I think so.

1738
01:52:43,722 --> 01:52:45,401
All right, see you in the winter then.

1739
01:52:45,746 --> 01:52:49,222
Yup, I'll read up on agriculture
for the next time I see you.

1740
01:52:49,866 --> 01:52:51,737
Huh?? Your not coming to ski?

1741
01:52:52,619 --> 01:52:54,784
The only way to learn is to do it, you know.

1742
01:52:55,417 --> 01:52:58,732
Give some thought to what we talked about, alrighty?

1743
01:52:58,862 --> 01:52:59,987
Huh?? What was that?

1744
01:53:00,394 --> 01:53:00,991
Yeah?

1745
01:53:01,708 --> 01:53:04,853
Don't you worry, that's between Taeko and me.

1746
01:53:05,789 --> 01:53:09,509
Hmm, did something go on yesterday between you two?

1747
01:53:10,095 --> 01:53:12,213
I'm sorry... And I'm fine.

1748
01:53:12,642 --> 01:53:15,251
Next time I won't bring along my 5th grade self.

1749
01:53:28,754 --> 01:53:29,960
Hold that train!

1750
01:53:31,990 --> 01:53:33,857
Take care of yourself, Naoko.

1751
01:53:42,847 --> 01:53:43,744
Goodbye.

1752
01:53:44,227 --> 01:53:45,106
Goodbye.

